Never stop pushing and learning 👊 
For years I have wanted to get back to dinner parties and events and finally we are bringing these intimate and special events to life in Austin at @wickedkitchenevents . 

Our Wicked Supper Series is going strong and slowly building momentum. So grateful for all that have and supported and joined us for a meal. 

Each month we have a theme, we do our research, we test, we research more, test more, and we showcase what we feel is a balanced representation of the cuisine showcased, with our Wicked twist and of course it always being vegan.

Our Wicked Supper Series is a way for us to show our passion for plants, while offering an experience to all that join us at our dinner table. 
The impact opportunity we have as chefs is enormous - pushing plants, showing that there is no reason animals need to suffer for us to enjoy a meal, and equally as important, bringing community together with a good meal and conversation. 

Our next supper club is Feb 23th, showcasing one my favorite cuisines and greatest culinary inspiration: Thailand. 🔥🌶️ 
hope to see you then

Finally! After a couple years, we are gardening again!
Nothing short of a labor of love getting this together, clearing the land, covering for a year, building, setting the beds and fence and finally planting our first seeds. So much work, but worth every minute that brought it together. Getting our hands in the dirt is the best medicine. 
Videos- Planting strawberry starts, greens, radishes and peas here. 
Will share progress with more videos to come, and do some IG lives for any questions that I may be able to support with, based on what not to do :) 

#wickedgarden #atx #gardening #texasgardening #growwhatyoucan

If it’s too early to sow directly, get some starts going on trays so you can easily move em around if you need to take them in. These dough boxes are perfect I just drilled holes into bottom for drainage. (Thank you @skullandcakebones fam). When each start has 4 or more true leaves they are ready to transplant. Fingers crossed it won’t frost again, hoping to get all of these into the ground in a week. 

Most of these seeds were about 2-3 years old so doubled up on how I planted in each container, turned out most sprouted 🎉

Always grow more than you need to share 💚

Beet charcuterie. 
Through many many trials we have some incredible cured, koji inoculated and aged beetroot charcuterie. 
Inspired and guided by @eddiesheps and the @nomaprojects fermentation book. So inspired by using Koji and the magic it can bring to vegetables, roots in particular. No wonder it’s been used for hundreds of years. I tried beetroot, carrots, rutabaga, parsnip, daikon and celeriac. Beet was definitely the favorite. It was a process, here’s some photos after it was peeled, cryovac, slow cooked, and cured in a salt brine for 5 days and coated in Koji and rice flour. 
In order or photos once the inoculating process was underway. 
- pic 1 &2: 24 hours in the chamber, smelling incredible 
- 36 hours in the chamber, the Koji has changed a bit and smell is sweeter 
- Weights taken to dehydrate to half its weight 
- After drying to half weight 
- Showing the fully finished product ready for tossing in olive oil and service 
- Final dish served with on the last supper club menu as a slice of it on top of cashew cheese mixed with dried orange, citrus frozen confetti, and finished with blood orange syrup. Was so fkn good. Thanks for the guidance on this one @eddiesheps, was worth the process. 

#beets #charcuterie #vegan #wickedsupperseries #plantpushers

Garden progress 💚
Amazed at how quickly things have taken off, in the next couple weeks we should be harvesting squashes, carrots, beets and cukes. 
Peas are in full force and lettuce has another couple weeks of enjoying before it’s too hot. Trellising and adding ash to the tomatoes seem to be the perfect match, can’t wait to see how these trellis in the weeks to come. 
Have learned that sprinklers are the worst for a lot of plants and may need to switch to drip lines, particularly any bush beans of any sort, burning the leaves (you can see em in the first bed). Everyday this garden teaches me so much
